@node not19 "AMIRC ON THE WWW LAUNCHED FROM IBROWSE"
                     AMIRC ON THE WWW LAUNCHED FROM IBROWSE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: "Jeff Pierce" <jeffanim5\@loop.com>

To All,
     For those of you who were curious about accessing IRC sites on the web and
wanted to do it with minimal effort, I have created a simple application using
AREXX, IBrowse, Perl, AmigaDOS & AmIRC together so when clicking on a channel
link you simply wait until these partners have finished their tasks, then you
can begin chatting.

I did this mainly because of another one of those "it can't be done unless
you're a PC" sites provided several IRC channels for access. In order for you to
use this setup, you should have:

     TCP/IP client (Miami, TermiteTCP, AmiTCP, etc.)
     AmIRC V3.5 (available at http://www.vapor.com/)
     IBrowse 2.2 (available at http://www.hisoft.com/)
     MUI 3.8 (available at http://www.sasg.com/)
     Perl V.5 (available on Aminet)
     AmigaDOS ( ;) )
     Arexx ( ;D )

To set up access in IBrowse, click on settings, general, ext. viewer. Set up
access to AmIRC as follows:

     MIME Type: application          Subtype: x-chat
     Extension: cha chat # &
     Viewer: "path to Arexx script"
     Arguments: NONE (do not put any arguments in this field, it's not needed.)

Here is the Arexx script that you can place anywhere, just make sure the viewer
in IBrowse points to it:

/* Get header information from IRC server */
options results
signal on syntax

address command "STACK 540000"
address command "wait 1 sec"
address command "failat 21"
address command "cd work:usr/bin/" /* This is the path to Perl */
address command "perl work:usr/lib/perl/irc.pl"  /* This is the path to the Perl script */
address command "STACK 4096"
exit

. . . . and now the Perl script:

$homedirectory = "ram:t/";
opendir(HOMEDIR, $homedirectory) ||
        die ("Unable to open directory");
while ($filename = readdir(HOMEDIR))
 {
        print ("$filename\n");
        if ($filename =~ /IBrowseTempFile/)
        { $tempfilename = $filename;
         last;
        }
}
die ("Unable to open temp file") unless open(INFILE,$homedirectory . $tempfilename);
closedir(HOMEDIR);
while ($inline =  )
{ chop ($inline);
 if ($inline =~ /SERVER\s(.*)/)
        {
        $servername = $1;
        }
 elsif ($inline =~ /CHANNEL\s(.*)/)
                {
                $channelname = $1;
                }
}
$command = "work:internet/amirc/amirc SERVER " . $servername . " autojoin " . $channelname . " CONNECT";
print "$command\n";
$execute = `work:internet/amirc/amirc SERVER "$servername" autojoin "$channelname" CONNECT`;
chop ($execute);
$delete = `workbench:c/delete ram:t/#? force all`;
chop ($delete);
exit(10);

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Now launch IBrowse and go to http://www.liszt.com/chat/. Select a channel of
interest and click on the link. The applications do the rest.

Admittedly this is a rather dirty solution but it gets the job done nicely.
Don't forget to set the stack size high (around 540k) for Perl or the system
will crash. Hope this is of aid to the Amiga community.

Kind Regards,

Jeff Pierce

And the world will know. . . . . .
