@node not29 "AMIWEST 2000 REPORT BY ACGREGORY"
                        AMIWEST 2000 REPORT BY ACGREGORY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

I went to the Amiwest show in Sacramento, CA for Saturday morning, and the
banquet on Saturday night. I would like to share tidbits of info I got. This
report will be far from complete, so any other info garnered by others will
hopefully illuminate my information. Since, I did not attend the whole show, nor
formally interview anyone, I cannot say the info is "official" although info
from the banquet has gotta be pretty much "official".

OK...let's go....

The exhibitors I saw were the following: UGN, Hyperion Games, Amiga-On-Line,
AmigaZone, Merlancia, AE Mail, FWD Computing, "Lostman", Compuquick, Soft-Logik,
Nova Design, Eyetech, Audiolabs, G&G Publishing, NAG, SACC. Boxer (Anti-Gravity)
had a booth, but there was rarely anyone in it.

   - UGN did the great live interview with Bill McEwan.

   - Hyperion was demoing Heretic. It looked very good, with very nice smooth
     panning and scenery shifting in 3D. The sound was good also.

   - AmigaZone: Harv Laser was there, trying to get people to join his excellent
     AmigaZone group. He was selling some nice 33.6K modems.

   - Merlancia: Good selection of hardware and software including SDK, OS 3.5. I
     am looking for a game, which they didn't have (it's about 6 years old), but
     they said they would look for it and give me a call if they find it...

   - AE Mail: John Zacharias and friends demoed the program AE mail live. I
     bought it from them, because it looks like a good program.

   - FWD Computing: Lots of software, especially CD titles.

   - LostMan: Selling lots of Amiga badged clothing. I wasn't too interested,
     but it looks like good quality.

   - Compuquick: Lots of software, hardware including a full spec developer
     station, the SDK, OS 3.5. They seemed to be very busy.

   - Soft-Logik were selling Pagestream 4 for Amiga/Mac/PC, along with upgrades.
     Unfortunately, it was SACC member manning the booth, not Deron K.
     (Soft-Logik) and on Saturday they did not have Pagestream 4 being demoed.
     Nevetheless I will upgrade to Pagestream 4, soon.

   - Nova Design: Kermit Woodall was their demoing the ImageFX 4. He was also
     selling Millenium, Wildfire, and Alladin. I will upgrade to IF4 soon.

   - G&G Publishing was giving out free copies of the latest issue of "The New
     Amigans", and signing up people for new subscriptions. Mr. Griffin is a
     very nice gentlemen, which an Amiga attitude, namely, if he sees a need,
     he tries to meet it. I wish him the best in this endeavour. I am confident
     he will succeed as long as there is news to be reported, and software and
     hardware to be reviewed.

   - Audiolabs was demoing their outstanding audio program.Was using the two
     screen output mode, and was also outputting one screen to a television.
     They were using a "Repulse" card for their audio. The program and sound
     card look like a winner. I will have to upgrade my Audiomaster software
     and and hardware to this eventually.

   - EyeTech: Alan Redhouse was demoing a rather cool device. It was a black
     box, about 18 inches long, 18 inches wide, and 4 inches tall. It contained
     the dev-box computer, along with a A1200 in it, with proper floppy and hard
     drive. The amiga side was running a Scala demo and outputting to a small
     flat screen monitor. The devbox was running the Elate "boing" demo and
     outputing to I believe a laptop type screen. It was very cool to see two
     computers outputting stuff like that. They also were selling software.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                      Final comment about the exhibitors:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

There was a casual, friendly atmosphere. No hype, or pressure sales. Everyone
was very helpful with questions. I am still impressed with the folks who attend
these shows, as they all are able to speak to computer issues with clear
evidence that they understand computers... they are not just consumers who will
buy any product as long as it is flashy or "new"... Quite a contrast from some
of the stores that sell PC's/MAC's etc. I also picked up an issue of Amiga
Active Magazine. It is a very worthy replacement for Amiga Format or CU Amiga.

OK, I hope I didn't leave anybody out. I also want to thank all the exhibitors
for showing up.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          AmiWest 2000 Banquet report
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

I attended the banquest Saturday night at Amiwest 2000. Here is brief report. I
hope I don't leave too much out, Bill McEwen does speak fast.

First off, the room was nice, with a very good buffet type serving method, and
the food was excellent.

The SACC gave the Ken Barton Memorial award for service excellence to the Amiga
community to John Zacharias. Well deserved, congratulations.

Bill McEwans talk was a rambling and fun talk with lots of nice demos and an old
Commodore videotape add featuring BB King, and others who were using the Amiga
in their professional work. It was clear, that at the timeof the tapes creation,
the Amiga was clearly the outstanding computer.

Mr. McEwen had three computers running. One of them was the ARM Prospector, a
solid state "laptop" not available commerically yet. He had two laptop clones,
one running Linux, the others from a large northwest USA company. What he did
was load code from a floppy on to each of them, and had them all running the
same program. He was attempting to demonstrate that the same code could be run
on different OS's and chips as long as it was written to the Amiga Foundation
layer. One could see how there were slight variations in the smoothless of some
on the animations when comparing with the different machines,but it was the same
animation. If that indeed was what was going onr, it was impressive since it was
a demo. However, as the specs of the machines were not known to myself, it was
hard to say how this would pan out. Nevertheless, it appears that something good
may be going on.

Mr. McEwen thanked all Amiga users, and developers, for keeping the platform
alive. He did this by giving all attendees of the banquest a T-Shirt which
wished Amiga a happy 15th birthday. The slogan on the back of the shirt reads,
"It took them 15 years to catch up...Now they never will" It also sported the
new Amiga SDK construction ball. Apparently there was some criticism that the
first SDK logo was kind of "Dark", so they tried to make it a bit more bright.

At the banquet, Mr. McEwan shared other bits of information:

   - New Staff
      - Bolton Peck is with Hardware QA
      - Bob Cozby (COZ) is also in QA
      - Paul Nolan (Photogenics fame) is on the GUI Team

   - There will be an IPO. He did not say when, he did not give an opening
     price.

   - Dean Brown is working on building a hardware laboratory at Amiga.

   - Amiga will design and build "spec" boards, systems, for OEM's, direct
     licensing or for their own use. They will build mother boards that make
     sense for the end developer.

   - They are working on JAVA implementation.

   - There will be a SDK developer kit that works with "that other OS" because
     many developers use that "other OS" to develop.

   - Many large firms, a veritable "Who's who" have bought the SDK.

   - He will appear with John Dvorak of a show called "Silicon Spring" from time
     to time....I wasn't quite sure how long this would go on (AG)

   - He said that it is helpful to compare where we have gotten in 7 months,
     versus 2 years from the last owners, so there is progress being made.

ROYALTY ISSUE!

The royalty program is VOLUNTARY. However, if any developer wants to work with
Amiga, there will be a royalty. This will give the developer "official" approved
status with Amiga.

The fee will be $1.50 per unit SOLD (not manufactured) or 5% of sales.

Mr. McEwan compared this to royalties from another software company where the
charge can be as high as $1 million dollars before any product is even shipped.
He mentioned that Sony charges royalty on what the developer manufactures(even
if the product is not sold).

Included in the royalty agreement, is help in marketing, advertising, and
product placement.

Continuing the information from the Saturday Banquet Ami West 2000....

   - By August, Amiga will assist anyone who wants to market Amiga paraphenalia.
     They will provide items at cost to those who want to market them. They will
     sell Amiga paraphenalia from their site also.

   - Advantages for buyng the official "d'Amiga"
     1. Free ticket to DevCon
     2. Proactive communication for "enhancements", bug fixes, etc.

   - SDK doesn't have sound, or 3D in it, but these areas will be added.

   - Amiga has not decided on the processor yet for the AmigaOne. They need a
     committment of 100,000 processors, so the roll-out date of XMAS cannot be
     fully confirmed.

   - Many of the features of Amiga OS that was liked will be moved on over to
     the SDK. He was not very specific about this.

   - The classic Amiga will be supported by something "better than an emulator".
     (I didn't know what he meant exactly....would it be hardware?, a dual
     computer, an Amiga PCI....??- AG)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                  CONCLUSIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From my perspective, (non-technical, non programmer, user) it would appear that
the Amiga is actually moving...slow, but moving.

Although many questions remain, (CPU for AmigaOne, SDK development in 3D, audio,
etc.) progress appears to be made by Amiga, Inc.

However, we have been down this path before, but this does seem to be much
further..(remember, Viscorp, Gateway)...

The thing that amazes me is the resiliency of the Amiga users/developers, who
still love using Amigas and developing for the community. People who are aware
of the power and usefulness of a incredibly well thought out and designed
computer (the Amiga, that is.)

I am hoping that I did an accurate report, and I am hoping that the statements I
heard and the demos I saw accurately reflect the present and future of
computing.
